<dl id="n25117c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n25" href="#n25117c">N25 (VI.B.15)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n25all.htm#n25117c"> 117(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> whisper word to H ecco! / crow flies</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">This being done, they returned to the Rishi, who made the husband sit down on the ground facing the East, and, having seated himself by his side, but with face to the West, <mark>whispered these two words</mark> in his ear, &ldquo;Namah Sivaya.&rdquo; Scarcely had Dasharha heard these marvellous words before <mark>a flight of crows</mark> was seen issuing from different parts of his body, these birds being the sins which he had committed.&rsquo; <small> Edward Clodd, <a name="ECTTT" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ECTTT"><cite title="source">Tom Tit Tot</cite></a> (1898) 203</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c14071j" href="c14all.htm#c14071j">VI.C.14:071(j)</a>, <a name="c14071k" href="c14all.htm#c14071k">VI.C.14:071(k)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
